# Project 2. Gobstones basics

Now, it's your turn to use Gobstones!
Build a program that, when the machine executes it, drop green stones in such a way as to form a winding 
line connecting the red stones, with a black stone in the last position, and remove the red stones:
we will say that the program "draws a snake that eats the apples".
That is, your program must indicate that, starting with the initial board on the left, produces the final 
board on the right.

We may imagine that the red stones are apples, and that the green and black stones form a snake.
The initial board is always the same, that is, all the apples are always at the same positions and the
initial cell is the one on the south-west corner.
So, we may say that the goal of the excercise is to draw a snake in such a way that it reaches
each of the apples, and it eats them in a fixed way.

Explore the environment to discover how to add built-in commands to a program, and how to execute that program.
You have to discover several things.
Those discoveries will allow you to make very intersting things.
(A hint: look into the toolbox on the left and experiment what different blocks can do!)

> **Some vocabulary**
>
> We call **initial board** to the board that the machine finds when starting the execution of the program.
> And the board that the machine produces after finishing the execution is called the **final board**.
> The **current cell** is the cell the one right below the **head** of the machine, and it's the only one where
> the head can perform any actions in the present moment.

&nbsp;

> **A matter of arguments**
>
> The built-in command `Poner` has a _hole_. 
> That hole has to be filled with a color.
> And colors, as well as directions, are data that is described through _expressions_.
> The value described by the expression that fills such a hole is called the **argument**. 
> For example, `Verde` is the argument in `Poner(Verde)`.
> The colors of stones in Gobstones are `Azul`, `Negro`, `Rojo` and `Verde`, 
>and the directions are `Norte`, `Este`, `Sur` and `Oeste`.
